First time here & a great experience! We got the veggie combo and the special kitfo which ended up placed in the center of the veggie combo. Everything was very good, with a variety of spice levels and flavors (even the salad was really good)! There were only two of us, and this was more than enough food (probably could have split across 3 people). They accept reservations (would recommend if you are planning ahead) and their website includes pictures of every dish. Several larger groups arrived after us which put a strain on the two servers, so I'd encourage you to be a little patient!

Now this is a hidden gem, and some of the best Ethiopian food I've had, in an area full of great Ethiopian food. We got the veggie combo and beef tibs, and everything was flavored perfectly (my complaint with some Ethiopian restaurants is that everything starts to taste the same, because it's the same spices liberally applies to lentils, and greens and chickpeas and cabbage... but not here). Things had flavor and that flavor had purpose. Also tried two Ethiopian beers out of the cooler and was please with both. Total bill for two, with beers, tax and tip was $40.  Also a great place to go with vegetarians.

My biggest complaint about most Ethiopian restaurants in our area is cleanliness. Beteseb has excellent food (and a bit less spice for us not accustomed to the stronger spices) and is very clean and well lit. Service was friendly and fast. You pick your beverages from a large cold case on one wall and they have a terrific range of beer options. We selected several Ethiopian beers and enjoyed all. If you order the vegetarian platter, consider adding the timatim salada (fresh tomato salad) as a side.

The food is very good and the restaurant has a welcoming casual atmosphere. Most dishes are served with injera, which is delicious. The portions are very large and two people could easily share a dish. They also have an excellent beer and wine selection, which includes Ethiopian beers (the Habesha beer is especially good). Expect to pay about $20 per person, which includes a drink tip.

Delicious Ethiopian food and great service. Not a lot of ambiance...it also has a small market selling coffee beans and chilled Ethiopian beers, among other things. and it was a little drafty in the winter, because of the layout in relation to the tables and the door. However, if you can deal with that, you will find yourself with generous portions of delicious (and, judging by the majority of the customers, also authentic) food. My date had a meat dish with coffee. I had a vegetarian sampler and a ginger tea. I was so excited to finally find a place with gluten free injera, so I could try Ethiopian food, and it did not disappoint. Definitely worth checking out.
